<span class="displaytext">arlington, va -- (candidate full) 2008 spokesman tucker bounds today issued the following statement on (candidate full)'s speech on the economy planned for this morning in new york city: <p>"no amount of rhetoric can hide senator (candidate last)'s clear record of embracing the liberal tax and spend, big government policies that hit hardworking american families at a time when they're most vulnerable, and are certain to move america backward. </p><p>"this election provides a clear choice. (candidate full) offers a common sense agenda to cut taxes, eliminate wasteful government spending, and get our economy back on track, while senator (candidate last) embraces the failed liberal policies of the past that lock down the ingenuity and entrepreneurial spirit that has always grown our economy, created jobs and expanded opportunity for the american people." <b><i> </i></b></p><p align="center">(candidate last)nomics: (candidate full)'s liberal tax &amp; spend, big government agenda  <b> </b></p><p align="center">(candidate last)'s high tax agenda <b><u> </u></b></p><p>(candidate last) has proposed a laundry list of tax hikes on the campaign trail, which would hurt the economy <i> </i></p><p> </p><p>(candidate last) has called for higher income taxes, social security taxes, investment taxes, and corporate taxes, as well as "massive new domestic spending." "(candidate last)'s transformation, if you go by his campaign so far, would mean higher income taxes, higher social security taxes, higher investment taxes, higher corporate taxes, massive new domestic spending, and a healthcare plan that perhaps could be the next step to a full-scale, single-payer system. is that what most americans want, someone who will fulfill a (PARTY NAME) policy wish list?" (james pethokoukis, "barack hussein reagan? ronald wilson (candidate last)?" <i>u.s. news &amp; world report</i>'s "capital commerce" blog, <a href="http://www.usnews.com/blogs/capital-commerce/2008/2/13/barack-hussein-reagan-ronald-wilson-(candidate last).html"><u> www.usnews.com</u> </a>, 2/12/08) </p><p></p><dir> <p>• <b> (candidate last) has also called for tax hikes on coal and natural gas.</b> (candidate last): "what we ought to tax is dirty energy, like coal and, to a lesser extent, natural gas." ("q&amp;a with sen. (candidate full)," <i>san antonio express-news</i>, 2/19/08) </p></dir><b><i> </i></b><p>the wall street journal's stephen moore: "if he becomes president — tax rates will go up almost across the board." "[(candidate last)] doesn't believe that raising tax rates is going to hurt the economy and if he becomes president ... tax rates will go up almost across the board." (<i>the wall street journal</i> website, <a href="http://online.wsj.com/public/page/8_0006.html?bcpid=86195573&amp;bclid=212338097&amp;bctid=1414665553/oblocked::http://online.wsj.com/public/page/8_0006.html?bcpid=86195573&amp;bclid=212338097&amp;bctid=1414665553"><u> www.wsj.com</u> </a> , accessed 2/13/08) </p><p>cnbc's larry kudlow: "[(candidate last)] has a very punitive high-tax campaign plan for the economy." (larry kudlow, "(candidate last), the very-high-tax candidate," <i>national review</i>'s "the corner" blog, <a href="http://corner.nationalreview.com/post/?q=yje1yjjln2q5zmyxotnlmdi2mmzmmdm2mgq4mthjymu"><u> nationalreview.com</u> </a>, 2/11/08) <b> </b></p><p>ben stein: "his understanding of economics is 100 percent wrong." "mr. (candidate last) could become president and derail everything because his understanding of economics is 100 percent wrong. ... i must say i'm so scared about mr. (candidate last) becoming president. i can hardly tell you." (cnbc's "kudlow &amp; company," 2/14/08) <b> <u> </u></b></p><p>(candidate last) said he will provide tax relief for working families, but voted for a budget that raises taxes on americans earning as little as $31,850  </p><p>(candidate last): "we could be fighting to put the american dream within reach for every american -- by